That new error came from how we were calling `Layer.provide`. In Effect the signature is curried—`Layer.provide(that)(self)`—so the first argument is the dependency layer, *then* you apply it to the layer that needs those dependencies. We had the parameters flipped:

```ts
const main = Layer.provide(server, dependencies);
// ^ sends the server into `that`, the dependencies into `self`
```

Because of that, all of the server’s requirements (`Config`, `SqlClient`, `RunHydrationQueue`, etc.) never actually got wired in, so `Layer.launch(main)` was still expecting them and TypeScript surfaced the “Missing … in the expected Effect context” + overload errors.

The fix is simply to call `Layer.provide` in the right order (or via `.pipe`):

```ts
const main = Layer.provide(dependencies)(server);
NodeRuntime.runMain(Layer.launch(main));
```

After swapping the arguments, the server layer now sees every dependency coming from `dependencies`, so `Layer.launch(main)` produces an `Effect<never, _, never>` and the compiler errors go away.

